<section xml:id="sec-derivative-implicit" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Implicit Differentiation</title>

<objectives>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Recognize when a relationship between <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> requires implicit differentiation 
      rather than treating <m>y</m> as an explicit function <m>y=f(x)</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
      Differentiate equations that involve both <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> by treating <m>y=y(x)</m>, 
      applying the Product Rule, Quotient Rule, and Chain Rule, and then solving for <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m>.
    </li>
    <li>
      Compute slopes of tangent lines and write equations of tangent lines for curves defined implicitly, 
      including identifying where tangents are horizontal or vertical.
    </li>
  </ul>
</objectives>


  <p>
    In earlier sections, we found tangent lines and rates of change by differentiating functions written in the form
    <m>y=f(x)</m>. However, many important curves are not given as explicit functions of <m>x</m>.
    Instead, they are described by equations that relate <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> implicitly.
    In this section, we develop a technique called <emph>implicit differentiation</emph> that allows us to
    compute derivatives directly from such equations.
  </p>

<subsection xml:id="ssec-implicit-motiv">
    <title>A Motivating Example</title>

    <p>
      Consider the circle defined by the equation <m>x^2+y^2=25</m>.
      If we wish to find the slope of the tangent line at the point <m>(3,4)</m>,
      we immediately face a difficulty: there is no function specified in the form <m>y=f(x)</m>.
    </p>

      <sidebyside width="60%">
        <figure xml:id="fig-implicit-circle-tangent">
  <caption>
    Tangent line to the circle <m>x^2 + y^2 = 25</m> at the point <m>(3,4)</m>.
  </caption>

  <image source="images/impDiff01.PNG" width="60%">
    <shortdescription>
      A coordinate plane showing the circle defined by x squared plus y squared equals 25.
      The circle is centered at the origin with radius 5.
      A dashed line represents the tangent line at the point (3,4),
      touching the circle at exactly one point.
      The point of tangency is marked, and the tangent line slopes downward to the right.
    </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>
      </sidebyside>
    

    <p>
      One possible approach is to make the equation explicit by solving for <m>y</m>. Let's consider this method first
    </p>

<example xml:id="ex-explicit-circle-tangent">

  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the slope of the tangent line to the circle
      <m>x^2+y^2=25</m> at the point <m>(3,4)</m> by first solving for
      <m>y=f(x)</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      We begin by solving the equation of the circle for <m>y</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      y = \pm\sqrt{25-x^2}.
    </me>

      <sidebyside width="60%">

<figure xml:id="fig-explicit-circle-branches">
  <caption>
    Explicit representations of the circle <m>x^2 + y^2 = 25</m> and the tangent line at <m>(3,4)</m>.
  </caption>

  <image source="images/impDiff02.PNG">
    <shortdescription>
      A coordinate plane showing the circle x squared plus y squared equals 25,
      written explicitly as two functions.
      The upper semicircle is shown as y equals the square root of 25 minus x squared,
      drawn as a solid red curve.
      The lower semicircle is shown as y equals negative the square root of 25 minus x squared,
      drawn as a dotted green curve.
      A dashed blue line represents the tangent line at the point (3,4),
      touching the upper semicircle at that point.
      The upper and lower branches are labeled to emphasize that the circle is not a single function of x.
    </shortdescription>
  </image>
</figure>


        </sidebyside>


    <p>
      This shows that the circle is the union of two function graphs. </p>




      <p> 
      Since the point <m>(3,4)</m> lies on the upper semicircle, we use
      <m>y=\sqrt{25-x^2}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Differentiate using the Chain Rule:
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{dy}{dx}
      =
      \frac{d}{dx}(25-x^2)^{1/2}
      =
      \frac12(25-x^2)^{-1/2}(-2x)
      =
      -\frac{x}{\sqrt{25-x^2}}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Evaluating at <m>x=3</m> gives
      <m>\frac{dy}{dx}=-\frac34</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>


<remark xml:id="rem-implicit-motivation">
  <p>
    While solving an equation for <m>y</m> can sometimes allow us to apply standard
    differentiation rules, this approach is often inconvenient and may even be
    impossible. In many equations, even relatively simple ones, such as <m>e^{y}=x+y</m>, the variable <m>y</m>
    appears in multiple locations and cannot be isolated as an explicit function
    of <m>x</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Implicit differentiation avoids this difficulty by treating <m>y</m> as a
    function of <m>x</m> and differentiating both sides of the equation directly,
    using the Chain Rule wherever <m>y</m> appears.
  </p>
</remark>



    <p>
      Instead of solving for <m>y</m>, we assume that <m>y=y(x)</m> is an unknown function of <m>x</m>
      that satisfies the equation. Then we can differentiate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>.
    </p>





<example xml:id="ex-implicit-circle-basic">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use implicit differentiation to find <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m> for the circle
      <m>x^2 + y^2 = 25</m>, and determine the slope of the tangent line at the point
      <m>(3,4)</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      We treat <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m> and differentiate both sides of the equation
      with respect to <m>x</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
        \dfrac{d}{dx}(x^2 + y^2) &amp;=&amp; \dfrac{d}{dx}(25) \\[0.6em]
        (x^2)' + (y^2)' &amp;=&amp; 0 \\[0.6em]
        2x + 2y\dfrac{dy}{dx} &amp;=&amp; 0.
      \end{array}
    </me>

<remark xml:id="rem-implicit-chain-rule">
  <p>
    The derivative <m>(x^2)' = 2x</m> follows from a basic derivative rule.
    In contrast, differentiating <m>y^2</m> requires the Chain Rule, since
    <m>y</m> is itself a function of <m>x</m>.
    Here the outside function is <m>(\ \ )^2</m> and the inside function is <m>y = y(x)</m>.
    As a result, the derivative introduces the unknown quantity <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m>,
    which we can then solve for algebraically.
  </p>
</remark>



    <p>
      We now solve for <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      \dfrac{dy}{dx} = -\dfrac{x}{y}.
    </me>

    <p>
      This derivative formula applies to <em>every</em> point on the circle.
      Evaluating at <m>(3,4)</m> gives
    </p>

    <me>
      \left.\dfrac{dy}{dx}\right|_{(3,4)} = -\dfrac{3}{4}.
    </me>
  </solution>
</example>

<p>
  Let us now formalize this process into a general technique.
</p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="implicit-diff-definition">
    <title>Key Idea: Implicit Differentiation</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-implicit-differentiation">
      <title>Implicit Differentiation</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <term>Implicit differentiation</term> consists of differentiating both sides of an equation with respect to <m>x</m>
          and then solving the resulting equation for <m>y'</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          In the examples and exercises of this section, it is assumed that the given equation determines <m>y</m> implicitly
          as a differentiable function of <m>x</m>, so that implicit differentiation applies.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <remark xml:id="rem-implicit-why">
      <p>
        The key feature is that <m>y</m> depends on <m>x</m>, even if the equation does not explicitly solve for <m>y</m>.
        So whenever you differentiate an expression containing <m>y</m>, you must use the Chain Rule and include a factor of <m>y'</m>.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example xml:id="ex-implicit-ln">
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given the equation <m>x\ln(y)+y^2=4x</m>, find <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}</m> using implicit differentiation.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Differentiate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>. The left side requires the Product Rule on <m>x\ln(y)</m>
          and the Chain Rule on <m>\ln(y)</m> and <m>y^2</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}\bigl(x\ln(y)\bigr)+\frac{d}{dx}\bigl(y^2\bigr)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}(4x)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle \Bigl(1\cdot \ln(y)+x\cdot \frac{1}{y}\,y'\Bigr)+2y\,y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 4.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Now solve for <m>y'</m> by collecting terms with <m>y'</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \frac{x}{y}\,y'+2y\,y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 4-\ln(y)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle y'\left(\frac{x}{y}+2y\right)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 4-\ln(y)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{4-\ln(y)}{\frac{x}{y}+2y}.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          A common simplification is to multiply top and bottom by <m>y</m>:
        </p>

        <me>
          \displaystyle y'=\frac{y(4-\ln(y))}{x+2y^2}.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

  

    <example xml:id="ex-implicit-tangent-line">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find an equation of the tangent line to the curve <m>y e^{\sin x}=x\cos y</m> at the point <m>(0,0)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Differentiate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>. Use the Product Rule on both sides.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}\bigl(ye^{\sin x}\bigr)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}\bigl(x\cos y\bigr)
\\[1.4em]
\displaystyle y'e^{\sin x}+y\cdot e^{\sin x}\cdot(\cos x)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 1\cdot \cos y + x\cdot \frac{d}{dx}(\cos y)
\\[1.4em]
\displaystyle y'e^{\sin x}+y e^{\sin x}\cos x
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \cos y + x\cdot\bigl(-\sin y\bigr)\,y'.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Now substitute <m>(x,y)=(0,0)</m>. Note <m>\sin(0)=0</m>, <m>e^0=1</m>, <m>\cos(0)=1</m>, and <m>\sin(0)=0</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle y'(1)+0
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 1+0
\\[0.8em]
\displaystyle y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 1.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          The slope at <m>(0,0)</m> is 1, so the tangent line is
        </p>

        <me>
          \displaystyle y=x.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

  <example xml:id="ex-implicit-astroid-like">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find <m>y'</m> if <m>y^3+x^3=6xy</m>. At what point in the first quadrant is the tangent line to this curve horizontal?
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Differentiate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>. On the right side, use the Product Rule on <m>6xy</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}(y^3)+\frac{d}{dx}(x^3)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{d}{dx}(6xy)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle 3y^2y'+3x^2
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 6\bigl(xy'+y\bigr)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle 3y^2y'+3x^2
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 6xy'+6y.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Solve for <m>y'</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle 3y^2y'-6xy'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 6y-3x^2
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle y'(3y^2-6x)
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 3(2y-x^2)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle y'
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \frac{3(2y-x^2)}{3y^2-6x}
\ =\ \frac{2y-x^2}{y^2-2x}.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          A horizontal tangent occurs when <m>\displaystyle y'=0</m>, which requires the numerator to be zero (and the denominator nonzero):
        </p>

        <me>
          \displaystyle 2y-x^2=0 \quad\Longrightarrow\quad y=\frac{x^2}{2}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Substitute <m>\displaystyle y=\frac{x^2}{2}</m> into the original equation <m>y^3+x^3=6xy</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \left(\frac{x^2}{2}\right)^3+x^3
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 6x\left(\frac{x^2}{2}\right)
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle \frac{x^6}{8}+x^3
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 3x^3
\\[1.2em]
\displaystyle \frac{x^6}{8}
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 2x^3.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          In the first quadrant, <m>x&gt;0</m>, so divide by <m>x^3</m>:
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
\displaystyle \frac{x^3}{8}
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 2
\\[0.8em]
\displaystyle x^3
\amp=\amp \displaystyle 16
\\[0.8em]
\displaystyle x
\amp=\amp \displaystyle \sqrt[3]{16}.
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Then
          <m>\displaystyle y=\frac{x^2}{2}=\frac{(\sqrt[3]{16})^2}{2}=\frac{\sqrt[3]{256}}{2}</m>.
          So the point in the first quadrant where the tangent is horizontal is
        </p>

        <me>
          \displaystyle \left(\sqrt[3]{16},\,\frac{(\sqrt[3]{16})^2}{2}\right).
        </me>

        <p>
          (This point is valid as long as <m>y^2-2x\neq 0</m>, which you can check holds here.)
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

  </subsection>
 

