    <exercisegroup xml:id="eg-implicit-explain">
  <title>Explain it to a Friend</title>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-implicit-when-needed">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Explain how to decide when implicit differentiation is needed to find <m>y'</m>, 
        as opposed to using the standard differentiation rules for explicit functions.
      </p>

      <p>
        In your explanation, include:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          One example where implicit differentiation is required.
        </li>
        <li>
          One example where implicit differentiation is <em>not</em> required, and standard rules apply directly.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        If you have a <m>y=f(x)</m> equation then you can just use the <em>normal</em> way but if <m>y</m> is not given explicitly as a function of <m>x</m>,
        and it is not easy to solve for a <m>y=f(x)</m> then implicit differentiation should be used 
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Example of when implicit differentiation is <em>not</em> needed: <me>y=x^2+e^x</me>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Example of when implicit differentiation is needed: <me>y=x^2+e^y</me>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p> 
      </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-geom-meaning-slope">
    <statement>
      <p>
        A student applies implicit differentiation to a curve and finds that <m>y'=5</m> 
        at the point <m>(x,y)=(1,2)</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Explain the geometric meaning of this result in terms of the graph of the curve.
        Your explanation should describe what this value tells you about the tangent line
        and the behavior of the curve near the point.
      </p>
    </statement>
        <solution>
      <p>
        The value <m>y'=5</m> at <m>(1,2)</m> means that the tangent line to the curve at that point has slope <m>5</m>.
        Geometrically, the curve is increasing at <m>(1,2)</m>, and very close to that point the graph rises about
        <m>5</m> units vertically for every <m>1</m> unit horizontally.
      </p>
    </solution>

  </exercise>

</exercisegroup>
<exercisegroup xml:id="eg-implicit-tf-computation">
      <title>True/False Questions</title>



  <exercise xml:id="tf-imp-ap-05">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>y=\ln(x+y)</m>, then implicit differentiation is required to find <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>True.</em> Since <m>y</m> appears on both sides of the equation, it is not possible to isolate <m>y</m>
        as an explicit function of <m>x</m> without also having <m>y</m> on the right side. Therefore, implicit differentiation
        is required to find <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>



    <exercise xml:id="tf-imp-ap-01">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>x^2+xy+y^2=7</m>, then <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}=-\frac{2x+y}{x+2y}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>True.</em> Differentiating both sides with respect to <m>x</m> gives
        <me>
          2x + \left(x\frac{dy}{dx} + y\right) + 2y\frac{dy}{dx} = 0.
        </me>
        Rearranging and solving for <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}</m> yields
        <me>
          \displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = -\frac{2x + y}{x + 2y}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>




  <exercise xml:id="tf-imp-ap-04">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>x\sin(y)=1</m>, then <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}=-\frac{\cos(y)}{x}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>False.</em> Differentiating both sides with respect to <m>x</m> gives
        <me>
          \sin(y) + x\cos(y)\frac{dy}{dx} = 0.
        </me>
        Rearranging and solving for <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}</m> yields
        <me>
          \displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = -\frac{\sin(y)}{x\cos(y)}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>




  <exercise xml:id="tf-imp-ap-07">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>e^{x+y}=x</m>, then <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}=\frac{1}{x}-1</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>False.</em> Differentiating both sides with respect to <m>x</m> gives
        <me>
          e^{x+y}\left(1+\frac{dy}{dx}\right) = 1.
        </me>
        Rearranging and solving for <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}</m> yields
        <me>
          \displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{1}{e^{x+y}} - 1.
        </me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

 

  <exercise xml:id="tf-imp-ap-09">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>x^2y+y^3=2</m>, then at <m>(1,1)</m> the slope of the tangent line is <m>-1</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>False.</em> Differentiating both sides with respect to <m>x</m> gives
        <me>
          2xy + x^2\frac{dy}{dx} + 3y^2\frac{dy}{dx} = 0.
        </me>
        Plugging in <m>(x,y)=(1,1)</m> gives
        <me>
          2(1)(1) + (1)^2\frac{dy}{dx} + 3(1)^2\frac{dy}{dx} = 0,
        </me>
        which simplifies to
        <me>
          2 + 4\frac{dy}{dx} = 0.
        </me>
        Solving for <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}</m> yields
        <me>
          \displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = -\frac{1}{2}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>


  <exercise xml:id="tf-imp-ap-11">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}=0</m> at a point on a curve defined implicitly, then the tangent line at that point is horizontal.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>True.</em> A slope of zero indicates that the tangent line is horizontal at that point on the curve.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="tf-imp-ap-12">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}</m> is undefined at a point on a curve defined implicitly, then the tangent line at that point is vertical.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>False.</em> While an undefined derivative often indicates a vertical tangent line, it can also occur at points where the curve has a cusp or corner.
        Therefore, an undefined derivative does not always imply a vertical tangent line.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="tf-imp-ap-13">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>x^2-y^2=1</m>, then the curve has a vertical tangent at points where <m>y=0</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>True.</em> Differentiating both sides with respect to <m>x</m> gives
        <me>
          2x - 2y\frac{dy}{dx} = 0.
        </me>
        Rearranging and solving for <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}</m> yields
        <me>
          \displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{x}{y}.
        </me>
        At points where <m>y=0</m>, the derivative is undefined, indicating a possible vertical tangent line. We must check if 
        such points lie on the curve. Setting <m>y=0</m> in the original equation gives <m>x^2=1</m>, 
        so the points <m>(1,0)</m> and <m>(-1,0)</m> are on the curve and we can verify with a graph that they have vertical tangents.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

<exercise xml:id="tf-imp-ap-14">
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>x^2+y^2=25</m>, then at <m>(3,4)</m> the second derivative <m>y''</m> is <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <em>False.</em> Differentiating both sides with respect to <m>x</m> gives
        <me>
          2x + 2y\frac{dy}{dx} = 0.
        </me>
        Solving for <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}</m> yields
        <me>
          \displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx} = -\frac{x}{y}.
        </me>
        Differentiating again with respect to <m>x</m> gives
        <me>
          \displaystyle \frac{d^2y}{dx^2} = -\frac{y - x\frac{dy}{dx}}{y^2}.
        </me>
        Substituting the value of <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}</m> and evaluating at <m>(3,4)</m> gives
        <me>
          \displaystyle y'' = -\frac{4 - 3\left(-\frac{3}{4}\right)}{16} = -\frac{4 + \frac{9}{4}}{16} = -\frac{\frac{25}{4}}{16} = -\frac{25}{64}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  
</exercise>


